Procedural blocks
- behavioural high level of verilog

Initial block
- will be executed only once, at first time the unit is called(only in testbench)
- we are going to do something at the beginning of simulation

intial begin
a=1'b0;
b=1'b0;
end

always block
- statement will be evaluated when a change in sensitivity lists occur
- sensitivity list, list of signal which causes whatever inside a block of code to be evaluated)

sync reset rising edge triggered flop
always @(posedge clock)
   if(!nreset)
      q <= 1'b0;
   else
      q <= d;

async reset rising edge triggered, load enable flop
always @(posedge clock or negedge nreset)
    if(!nreset)
       q <= 1'b0;
    else if(load_enable)
       q <= d;

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
There are two type of always block -
1) Sequential 
- asserted by a clock in the sensitivity list
- translate into flip flop and latches

always @(posedge clock or negedge nreset)
   if(!nreset)
     q <= 1'b0;
   else if(load_enable)
     q <= d;

2) Combinational 
- describe purely combinational logic and therefore the sensitivity list has (non-clock) signals
- the verilog 2001 standard allows using * instead of a sensitivity list to reduce bugs.

always @(a or b or c)
  out = a & b & c;

always @(*)
  out = a & b & c;

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Assignments
3 types of assignment

1) continous assignment
- outside of always block

assign muxdut = sel ? in1 : in0;

2) blocking procedural assignment "="
- rhs is executed and assignment is completed before the next statement is executed

// assume initially a=1
a=2;
b=a;
output =>  a=2, b=2

3) non-blocking procedural assignment "<="
- rhs is executed and assignment takes place at the end of current time step

// assume initially a=1
a=2;
b=a;
output => a=2, b=1

Rules
- combinational always block - use blocking assignment "="
- sequential always block - use non-blocking assignment "<="
- don't mix blocking and non-blocking in the same always block
- don't assign to the same variable from more than one always block

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hierarchy

Modules -
used to define a hardware block

Module mux4(out,in,sel);
  input [3:0] in;
  input [1:0] sel;
  output out;
  reg out;
  always @(*)
   case(sel)
      2'b00 : out = in[0];
      2'b01 : out = in[1];
      2'b10 : out = in[2];
      2'b11 : out = in[3];
      default : out = 4'bx;
   endcase
endmodule

Instance -
referencing a block at a different level

mux4 m0(.out(outa), .in(a), .sel(sel));

